<section xml:id="review-solving-quadratic-equations">

    <title>Solving Quadratic Equations Chapter Review</title>

    <subsection>
        <title>Solving Quadratic Equations by Factoring</title>
        <p>In <xref ref="section-solving-quadratic-equations-by-factoring" text="title">this section</xref> we covered the <xref ref="fact-zero-product-property" text="title">zero product property</xref> and learned an algorithm for <xref ref="algorithm-solving-quadratic-equations-by-factoring" text="title">solving quadratic equations by factoring</xref>.</p>

        <example>
            <title>Solving Using Factoring</title>
            <statement>
                <p>Solve the quadratic equations using factoring.
                    <ol>
                        <li><p><m>x^2-2x-15=0</m></p></li>
                        <li><p><m>4x^2-40x=-96</m></p></li>
                        <li><p><m>6x^2+x-12=0</m></p></li>
                        <li><p><m>(x-3)(x+2)=14</m></p></li>
                        <li><p><m>x^3-64x=0</m></p></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>Solve the quadratic equations using factoring.
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>Use factor pairs.
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>x^2-2x-15\amp=0</mrow>
                                    <mrow>(x-5)(x+3)\amp=0</mrow>
                                </md>
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>x-5\amp=0 \amp\text{ or }\amp\amp x+3\amp=0</mrow>
                                    <mrow>x\amp=5 \amp\text{ or }\amp\amp x\amp=-3</mrow>
                                </md>
                            So the solution set is <m>\{5,-3\}</m>.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>Start by putting the equation in standard form and factoring out the greatest common factor.
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>4x^2-40x\amp=-96</mrow>
                                    <mrow>4x^2-40x+96\amp=0</mrow>
                                    <mrow>4\left(x^2-10x+24\right)\amp=0</mrow>
                                    <mrow>4(x-6)(x-4)\amp=0</mrow>
                                </md>
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>x-6\amp=0 \amp\text{ or }\amp\amp x-4\amp=0</mrow>
                                    <mrow>x\amp=6 \amp\text{ or }\amp\amp x\amp=4</mrow>
                                </md>
                            So the solution set is <m>\{4,6\}</m>.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>Use the AC method.
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>6x^2+x-12\amp=0</mrow>
                                    <intertext>Note that <m>a\cdot c=-72</m> and that <m>\highlight{9\cdot-8}=-72</m> and <m>\highlight{9-8}=1</m></intertext>
                                    <mrow>6x^2\substitute{+9x-8x}-12\amp=0</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\left(6x^2+9x\right)+\left(-8x-12\right)\amp=0</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\highlight{3x}\left(2x+3\right)\mathbin{\highlight{-4}}\left(2x+3\right)\amp=0</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\left(2x+3\right)\highlight{\left(3x-4\right)}\amp=0</mrow>
                                </md>
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>2x+3\amp=0 \amp\text{ or }\amp\amp \highlight{3x-4}\amp=0</mrow>
                                    <mrow>x\amp=-\frac{3}{2} \amp\text{ or }\amp\amp x\amp=\highlight{\frac{4}{3}}</mrow>
                                </md>
                            So the solution set is <m>\{-\frac{3}{2},\frac{4}{3}\}</m>.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>Start by putting the equation in standard form.
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>(x-3)(x+2)\amp=14</mrow>
                                    <mrow>x^2-x-6\amp=14</mrow>
                                    <mrow>x^2-x-20\amp=0</mrow>
                                    <mrow>(x-5)(x+4)\amp=0</mrow>
                                </md>
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>x-5\amp=0 \amp\text{ or }\amp\amp x+4\amp=0</mrow>
                                    <mrow>x\amp=5 \amp\text{ or }\amp\amp x\amp=-4</mrow>
                                </md>
                            So the solution set is <m>\{5,-4\}</m>.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>Even though this equation has a power higher than <m>2</m>, we can still find all of its solutions by following the algorithm. Start by factoring out the greatest common factor.
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>x^3-64x\amp=0</mrow>
                                    <mrow>x\left(x^2-64\right)\amp=0</mrow>
                                    <mrow>x(x-8)(x+8)\amp=0</mrow>
                                </md>
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>x\amp=0 \amp\text{ or }\amp\amp x-8\amp=0 \amp\text{ or }\amp\amp x+8\amp=0</mrow>
                                    <mrow>x\amp=0 \amp\text{ or }\amp\amp x\amp=8 \amp\text{ or }\amp\amp x\amp=-8</mrow>
                                </md>
                            So the solution set is <m>\{0,8,-8\}</m>.</p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

